<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT26-B38-20</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA060-000326-B012-394</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.mediaresearch.org:80/nationalreview/daily/nr112396.html 204.71.237.92 19970115004243 text/html 6505
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 15-Jan-97 00:42:43 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 26-Nov-96 00:12:18 GMT
Content-length: 6318
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 23, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Boys Will Be Boys</b><br>
For some reason, <I>Washington Times</I> columnist Wesley Pruden delights in sexual slurs against his assorted enemies: "They're not real men" is his constant theme, even when he's discussing women. Normally this is harmless enough. But it takes a particularly ugly twist in today's column, "Trashy talk can have its rewards." Pruden writes, "Only this week a court in Eau Claire, Wis., awarded a 21-year-old man a million dollars for 'pains and slights' suffered at the hands of his high-school chums, who razzed him because he was a homosexual who prefers lads to lassies. Such a deal. An award of a million dollars just to be the butt of a joke is enough to make anyone cheerful, if not gay. This kind of stuff could be catching, and there's even a government agency to make whiners feel good about themselves." Pruden's version of events is misleading on several counts. The award was $900,000; and it was an out-of-court settlement. But the real distortion is his out-of-context use of the phrase "'pains and slights'" and his own words "razzed" and "whiners." The man in this casea boy at the time, let's rememberwasn't just "razzed." He was shoved, spat upon, beaten, and urinated on. He was kicked in the abdomen so many times he required surgery. A good case can be made that awards and settlements shouldn't be this generous. But Pruden doesn't advance that case. Nor does he do a service to those conservatives who harbor moral objections to homosexual behavior and are unjustly accused of vile bigotry.
<P>
<b>Affirmative Distraction</b><br>
The latest <I>New Yorker</I> includes an essay by Alan Wolfe on affirmative action. Like a lot of writing on the subject, it focuses on race preferences to the exclusion of gender preferenceswhich is odd, since the latter is far more significant by many measures. The article has its insights, but it is marred by conceptual confusions and ignorance of the conservative movement. 
<P>
Most of the article is devoted to exploring the alleged implications of corporate America's attachment to racial preferences. He writes that "the right doesn't want to admit that affirmative action has the blessing of the marketplace." "In fact, there are no conservative arguments against the most effective and prevalent forms of affirmative action in America, those implemented by companies." This is, at the very least, muddled. It is simply erroneous to assume that all practices in the private sector are necessarily free-market phenomena: like HMOs, race preferences are at least partly an adaptation to an environment created by the government. Quotas, that is, prevent lawsuits alleging the infringement of state-created "rights." Quite a few conservatives would not have (political) objections to truly voluntary affirmative action, which would be neither required nor encouraged by the government. Clint Bolick, a leading libertarian foe of preferences whom Wolfe never mentions, has said as much; Dinesh D'Souza incorporated an argument along those lines in the conclusion of his much-excoriated <I>The End of Racism</I>.
<P> 
Wolfe's argument becomes slippery when he writes that "conservatives have only two choices: to become liberals if they are to reject affirmative action in the private sector, or to accept such affirmative action if they are to remain conservatives. So why haven't more conservatives endorsed affirmative action? One answer is that a surprising number of them haveor, at least, did. Even the Reagan Administration, for all its professed opposition to affirmative action, adopted the practice of 'race-norming'; that is, raising the scores of minorities on standardized tests to make them more comparable with the scores of whites." He then writes about the Nixon Administration's role in fostering preferences, which he says conservatives don't like to admit. This entire passage is, not to put too fine a point on it, nonsense. The practice of "race-norming" is not the sort of "affirmative action in the private-sector" that conservatives are supposedly obligated to support; and conservatives, who have no love for Nixon's domestic politics, almost always mention his role in the history of race preferences when they write about the subject.
<P> 
Wolfe's thesis collapses at the finish line. "Without governmental enforcement," he writes, "some private companies may indeed drop their enthusiasm for diversity and retreat to 'birds of a feather' hiring policies." If that's the case, how can it be said that affirmative action "has the blessing of the marketplace"? Plenty of conservatives, though not all of us, would have no problem with Wolfe's conclusion that "while it makes sense for government to aspire to color blindness in order to underscore the importance of universality, companies and private universities ought to be free to take race into account for reasons of pluralism." Here is what <I>NR</I> said about the subject in its August 14, 1995 issue: "Conservatives may argue among themselves over whether purely voluntary, private affirmative action should be banned (as adherence to the Civil Rights Act of 1964 would require), but market forces would probably minimize such discrimination once [government regulations encouraging it were eliminated]." Wolfe is clearly the type of liberal who likes to think that ideas that complex never occur to conservatives.

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
