<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>Washington Bulletin</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 21, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Ominous News</b><br>
American Enterprise Institute pollster Karlyn Bowman isn't sure what to make of the trend, but it appears that public opinion toward government is softening. This could be, she says, a "prosperity effect": people tend to worry less about runaway government during good times. But might it also suggest a general flabbiness in Republicans' pressing the limited-government case these days?
<P>
<b>For Worse</b><br>
The <I>Washington Post</I> Style section today carries a front-page story on a wedding, titled "Every Girl's Dream." That ought to be enough information for our readers to figure out that the wedding concerned pairs two lesbians. (Heterosexual marriages don't warrant Style treatment unless they involve celebrities.) One woman's family plans to attend; the other woman's family is torn between, guess what, love and prejudice. You could, in other words, write the article half-asleep. ABC's <I>20/20</I> did a segment on same-sex marriages, cleverly titled "For Better or Worse," a few weeks ago. ABC at least allowed family members opposed to same-sex marriage to have a say; but of course, none of them were articulate. Under no circumstances is an articulate traditionalist case allowed on the air. Since it looks like the gay-rights side is going to win in a matter of years anyway, why not say conservatives surrender now, and spare ourselves an endless stream of saccharine documentaries?
<P>
<B>Word to the Wise</b><br>
<I>National Review</I> is sponsoring a forum at the Heritage Foundation next Tuesday, 24 p.m., on the politics of abortion. Does the Republican Party's pro-life stance hurt its political prospects, as is often claimed? Ann Stone, head of Republicans for Choice, and Jim Pinkerton will argue that it does and should be changed. Columnist Maggie Gallagher and Frank Cannon, of Lehrman Bell Mueller Cannon, will argue the contrary position. Karlyn Bowman of the American Enterprise Institute will walk us through poll data on the subject. And <I>NR</I>'s own Kate O'Beirne will moderate. Come one, come all.


<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
