<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I> for November 5, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>NR Washington's Election Predictions</b><br>
	Pundits all around the country are weighing in with their election predictions, here is NR Washington's Stab at Prognostication:
<P>
	The Presidency: Bill Clinton, of course, wins in a walk, but a closer walk than people think. The president will be held below 50 per centprobably the 4748 rangedealing a blow to his plans to claim an election mandate (the press may well give him one anyway). Dole has been closing in recent days thanks to the Indonesian scandals. The word is that Dole internal polls have him within 6 points in California, which he must win if he is going to pull off his electoral-vote inside straight. But it's too late for him to win there. The campaign has also been taking heart from the Reuters/Zogby poll which has Dole down by just 4 point nationally. But most other tracking polls have Clinton up by 9-16 points, and with the President leading in Republican states like Arizona and Florida he is assured a very pleasant election evening. The Senate: Republicans gain two or three seats. Republicans will pick up seats in the South; they will certainly win the open Howell Heflin seat in Alabama, are likely to win the David Pryor seat in Louisiana, and have a chance to win Democratic open seats in Georgia (Republican Guy Millner has pulled even with Max Cleland) and Louisiana (Republican Woody Jenkins is tied with Mary Landrieu). Meanwhile, the only Republican incumbent who will lose is Sen. Larry Pressler who is trailing in South Dakota. Sen. Bob Smith will pull it out in New Hampshire, and Sen. Jesse Helms will be fine in North Carolina. Get ready for some more troops for Trent Lott (and they'll be more conservative too). The House: Republicans lose 5-7 seats tops and could even make some gains. The tide has clearly shifted the Republicans' way at the congressional level, thanks in part to a huge barrage of negative advertising against the Democrats. There are only 10 or so Republican freshmen who seem sure to lose. There are another nearly 30 seats where the Democrats have a chance, but these potential Democratic gains are easily offset by 10 Democratic seats where the GOP seems likely to make pick-ups and another roughly 20 where the Republicans have a chance. When all the dust settles the situation in the House will look much the way it does nowwith one important exception. By early summer, one way or another, Newt Gingrich will no longer be Speaker. 

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
