<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I> for November 1, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Holding The House and Senate?</b>
All right: here's some (possible) good news for a change. As of yet there's no sign of a national Democratic tide that would sweep the party back into control of the Senate and House. Although Republicans are still warily eyeing Clinton's final all-out campaign push, they are encouraged by trends in Senate and House races. In Senate races in Nebraska, Montana, and Iowa Republicans have made big gains in the last week in seats being defended by the Democrats. Presumablyalthough no one can say anything for surethe trend would be the opposite if Clinton were building a national Democratic wave. In the House the trend is similar. The kind of freshmen Democrats will have to beat to regain the majority have built leads over their opponents in recent weeks: Phil English and Jon Fox in Pennsylvania and Bob Ney, Steve Chabot and Steven La Tourette in Ohio. Republicans think a number of factors are working in their favor as the campaign draws to a close. 1) The message that Bill Clinton shouldn't be given a "blank check" with a Democratic Congressthe National Republican Campaign Committee is running ads to this effect in 50 House racesseems to be taking hold. 2) The continuing high-profile Asian fundraising scandal increases uneasiness with Clinton and supports the idea he can't be trusted with a Democratic Congress. 3) The Republican national committees are finally unleashing a tide of spending across the country, the National Rifle Association is kicking in a late $1.5 million independent expenditure, and Republican candidates have tended to save their resources, until now, for the final push. 4) The Christian Coalition will presumably be turning out voters big-time in an election everyone agrees will hinge largely on turn-out. 5) Perot seems to be gaining ground, and if his voters show up at the polls they will tend to vote for GOP congressional candidates. But Republicans should hold their breath until they actually cross the finish line. What they all dread is a smashing Clinton victory in the East, trumpeted by the networks around 8 p.m. eastern-time or so, which keeps Republicans away from the polls everywhere else. If that happens, despite everything, it might be time to start saying "Speaker Gephardt." (Uh, that's the bad news.) 
 

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
