<TITLE>Mandate for Leadership IV -- Heritage Bookstore</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#00009C" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00">
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=5>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=CENTER>
<img src="/heritage/mandate/mandate.gif" width=250 height=379 align=left hspace=10 alt="Mandate for Leadership IV book cover">
</TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER>
<H2><FONT COLOR="red">MANDATE FOR LEADERSHIP IV<BR>
<I>Turning Ideas Into Actions</FONT></I></H2>
<B>By Stuart M. Butler and Kim R. Holmes</B>

<P>
<a href="/heritage/mandate/toc.html">Table of Contents</a></CENTER>

<P>
The Heritage Foundation's <I>Mandate for Leadership</I> series of policy handbooks, launched in 1981, explains how to get things done in Washington.  This fourth in the series, "Turning Ideas Into Actions," is the first <I>Mandate</I> aimed primarily at Congress.  In 1994, the voters elected  a Congress that was more conservative and more committed to fundamental change in the way Washington operates.  But while important reforms were enacted, Congress was outmaneuvered in its efforts to achieve structural change in many important areas, such as Medicare. The task for the new 105<sup>th</sup> Congress will be not so much to identify a brand new agenda, but to develop a more effective strategy to implement a conservative agenda already endorsed by the American people in two elections.  

<P>

This <I>Mandate</I> is a lawmaker's handbook for achieving policy objectives.  Drawing on the experience of dozens of legislative specialists and former government officials -- the doers of the last 20 years -- it looks at the hard lessons learned and lays out a practical strategy to build bipartisan and public support for a reform agenda based on conservative principles. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H2><FONT COLOR="red">Comments on <I>Mandate for Leadership IV:<BR> Turning Ideas Into Actions</I></FONT></H2></CENTER>

<P>
"<I>Mandate for Leadership</I> provides a fresh and valuable perspective on a wide-range of important issues."
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Representative Dick Armey, House Majority Leader</B>
</UL>
<P>
"This book is a terrific volume of practical solutions to real problems facing Americans."
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Representative John Boehner, Chairman, House Republican Conference</B>
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER><H2><FONT COLOR="red">Comments on earlier <I>Mandates</I></FONT></H2></CENTER>
<P>
The <I>Mandate</I> volumes played a major role in shaping policy during the Reagan-Bush era. <I>The Washington Post</I> called the first <I>Mandate</I> -- which was hand-delivered to the incoming Reagan Cabinet soon after the 1980 election -- "the bible of the Reagan transition."  <I>The New York Times</I> called <I>Mandate</I> "the hottest ticket in town."  And <I>National Review</I> described the policy tome as "an Owner's Manual for the Federal Government."  Trent Lott, then House Minority Whip said <I>Mandate</I> was "unparalleled in scope."

<P>
<CENTER><H2><FONT COLOR="red">Ordering Information</FONT></H2></CENTER>

760 pages. Price: $33.95 hardcover, $28.95 softcover (includes shipping and handling)
<P>
To order, call Heritage Publications toll-free at 1-800 544-4843, or email <a href="mailto:pubs@heritage.org">pubs@heritage.org</a>
