<li>    Bureau of Labor Statistics, Internet site <a href="ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt"> ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt</a>.<p>
<li>    Taking into account that 88 percent of the cost of all legally required benefits is shifted to workers in the form of reduced cash pay and that some workers receive Social Security benefits, the net cost of the tax wedge for workers is between $3.81 and $3.69 per hour, or at least 21.6 percent of a worker's total compensation.<p>
<li>    Bureau of Labor Statistics, Internet site <a href="ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt"> ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt</a>.<p>
<li>    Taking into account that 88 percent of the cost of all legally required benefits is shifted to workers in the form of reduced cash pay and that some workers receive Social Security benefits, the net cost of the tax wedge for manufacturing workers is between $4.43 and $4.32 per hour, or at least 21.1 percent of a worker's total compensation.<p>
<li>    Bureau of Labor Statistics, Internet site <a href=" ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt"> ftp://stats.bls.gov/pub/news.release/ecec.txt</a>.<p>
<li>    Taking into account that 88 percent of the cost of all legally required benefits is shifted to workers in the form of reduced cash pay and that some workers receive Social Security benefits, the net cost of the tax wedge for service-producing workers is between $3.47 and $3.36 per hour, or at least 21.2 percent of a worker's total compensation.<p>
<li>    Heritage Foundation estimate of hourly cash wages plus employer-paid taxes for legally mandated benefits. Although some employers provide optional benefits to minimum wage workers, accurate estimates of the cost are not available.<p>
<li>    U.S. Chamber of Commerce, "Employee Benefits Historical Data," 1982, and "Employee Benefits Survey," 1994.<p>
<li>    Mark Wilson, "Wages, Profits, and Income: Politics vs. Reality," <a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/fyi97.html">Heritage Foundation <I>F.Y.I.</I> No. 97</a>, April 19, 1996.<p>
